The paper deals with density estimation, which is a common topic in machine learning and falls under the category of cs.LG (Machine Learning). The use of total variation distance and tail decay rates suggests a connection to information theory, making cs.IT (Information Theory) another likely sub-category. The algorithmic nature of the paper and the focus on rates of convergence suggest a connection to computational complexity, making cs.CC (Computational Complexity) a possible sub-category. The use of shift-invariant distributions and the study of their properties suggest a connection to signal processing, making cs.SI (Signal Processing) a possible sub-category. Finally, the study of multidimensional distributions and the use of sample complexity lower bounds suggest a connection to data structures and algorithms, making cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) another possible sub-category.
